As he left after the short hearing, he told reporters inside the court building that he could not talk about the case.

He said: 'I either talk for a long time or I don’t, and at the moment I’m not talking.'

Addressing reporters outside court, 
Travis added: 'I am supported by my wife and friends. My wife is not here
today and the reason that she is not here today is because I detest 
hare-coursing.'

Travis has denied any wrongdoing since he was first arrested on 
suspicion of sexual offences last November.

When prosecutors announced the charges, his lawyer Martin Bale released a statement to say: 'Mr Travis is naturally disappointed that charges have been preferred and we will be taking stock of the position in the coming weeks once we have full details of the prosecution case.

'Mr Travis denies the allegations and looks forward to having the opportunity to clear his name.' 

